# Foundations

These are the baseline conventions all engineers follow regardless of role or stack.

## Code Style

- Use explicit, readable names over clever abbreviations
- No magic numbers or strings — extract to named constants
- One concern per file; avoid god modules and god classes
- Prefer flat structures over deeply nested ones
- Delete dead code; do not comment it out and leave it

## Naming Conventions

- Files: `kebab-case`
- Classes / types: `PascalCase`
- Functions / variables: `camelCase` (JS/TS) or `snake_case` (Python)
- Boolean variables: prefix with `is_`, `has_`, or `can_`
- Constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`

## Git Workflow

- Commits follow Conventional Commits: `feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`, `test:`, `docs:`, `refactor:`
- Subject line: imperative mood, max 72 characters
- One logical change per commit — do not batch unrelated fixes
- Branch naming: `feat/`, `fix/`, `chore/` prefixes followed by a short descriptor

## Pull Requests

- One concern per PR; do not mix feature work with refactors
- Every PR must have a description explaining the *why*, not just the *what*
- Link to any relevant issue or ticket

## Secrets and Configuration

- Never hardcode credentials, API keys, or secrets in source code
- Use environment variables for all configuration that differs between environments
- Never commit `.env` files — provide a `.env.example` instead

## Dependencies

- Pin versions in lock files
- Document in the PR description why a new dependency was added
- Prefer standard library or existing dependencies over adding new ones for small tasks

## Documentation

- Every project must have a `README.md` with: purpose, setup instructions, and how to run tests
- Document *why* a non-obvious decision was made, not *what* the code does
